# Why I Started the 100 Apps Challenge

One of the reasons I decided to do the 100 apps challenge, is because I got stuck between 3 paths for Storybookly.

## 1. The Gift Business

I started Storybookly originally because 2 years ago, I wanted to give my nephew a little short story about himself for his birthday. Instead of just 1 book, I thought about creating a startup out of it.

However, along the way I realized that I am actually not a fan of the gift-giving-business-model.

People find it once, buy something, and then never visit again (so zero retention).

Additionally, there were also some extra risks included with this that I had not thought about before, and I did not want to go that path yet.

## 2. Everyday Personalized Reading

So then I wanted to switch to a everyday-personalized-reading tool.

However, when you buy a gift, people buy it on the web. When parents read to their child everyday, they do this on a tablet or smartphone. So this means, the medium suddenly changed: from web to app.

However, it might sound easy to switch to that, but it’s more difficult than you would expect. Mainly because Google and Apple have their own set of rules that you need to comply with and the tools to transform web to apps aren’t very good.

## 3. Writers

Then there is also the third path: writers.

I am myself a huge fan of creating content and if I had to use the tool, I would use it as a writing tool.

However, just like the other 2, this one also came with some tradeoffs: writers want way more control over their book. I had already done some editing tools in the beginning, but I quit that after it was more difficult than expected.

Nowadays, I do actually have a very good solution to solve what I couldn’t solve 2 years ago, but the thought of having to make all the features that writers want… then the app suddenly becomes “complex” and I don’t want that.

A good thing about the writers app is that they also prefer it on the web, which Storybookly already is.

## 3 Choices

So there it is: 3 choices. 3 choices I could not choose between.

Not being able to choose between them is part of what pushed me into building 100 apps instead.

Now I don’t have to choose anymore.

I just do.
